\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\noindent
1.
 Prove that the eigenvalues of a symmetric matrix are real.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Assume the the contrary (i.e.
 that A is symmetric and that A has at least one non real eigenvalue).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
By definition, eigenvalues must satisfy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Ax=\lambda x
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align block
By assumption, both sides of the above equation are complex.
 Therefore, we can now assert that their complex conjugates must also be
 equal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Thus, denoting the complex conjugates by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

, we can see that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\hat{x}=\hat{\lambda}\hat{x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
By premultiplying both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}'$
\end_inset

 and from the multiplication of complex numbers, we gain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{x}'Ax-x'A\hat{x}=(\lambda-\hat{\lambda})\hat{x}'x
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align block
Since A is symmetric, the left side of the equation equals zero.
 This implies that the right side must also equal zero, but since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}'x$
\end_inset

 can never be equal to zero it must be that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\hat{\lambda}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Hence, lambda equals its conjugate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Thus lambda must be real.
\end_layout

