\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\noindent
i.
 Show that any entry in O is between -1 and 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Assume that O is an nxn orthogonal matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow O^{T}O=I_{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Since diagonal elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}$
\end_inset

 are all equal to one, the following must be true for all j
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{j=1}{\overset{n}{\sum}}O_{ij}^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Thus, no single entry in any row i can exceed one in absolute value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Since this statement is true for all i, then no entry in orthogonal matrix
 O can exceed 1 in absolute value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\noindent
ii.
 Show that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvalue of O, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mid\lambda\mid=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Since O is orthogonal, it satisfies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $AA^{T}=I_{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow A^{-1}=A^{T}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Since the eigenvalues of a matrix are equal to the eigenvalues of that matrix's
 transpose, we know that the eigenvalues of A are equal to the eigenvalues
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{T}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
From here, we can see that the eigenvalues of A are equal to the eigenvalues
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
We also know that the eigenvalues of an inverse matrix are equal to the
 reciprocals of that matrix itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Thus, the eigenvalues of A are equal to their own reciprocals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
This implies that the eigenvalues of A must be either 1 or -1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mid\lambda\mid=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\noindent
iii.
 Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $det(O)=\pm1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Since O is orthogonal, it satisfies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $OO^{T}=I_{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $det(OO^{T})=det(I_{n})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $det(O)det(O^{T})=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $(det(O))^{2}=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $det(O)=\pm1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

